<DIV TYPE="slide"><HEAD>Goals of the TEI</HEAD>
<LIST><ITEM>better interchange and integration of data</ITEM>
<ITEM>support for <EMPH>all</EMPH> texts, in <EMPH>all</EMPH>
languages, from <EMPH>all</EMPH> periods</ITEM>
<ITEM>guidance for the perplexed:  <EMPH>what</EMPH> to encode</ITEM>
<ITEM>assistance for the specialist:  <EMPH>how</EMPH> to encode any
information of interest</ITEM></LIST></DIV>
<DIV TYPE="slide"><HEAD>TEI Deliverables</HEAD>
<P><LIST><ITEM>A coherent set of recommendations for text encoding<LIST
>
<ITEM>comprising several distinct SGML tag sets</ITEM>
<ITEM>based on existing practice</ITEM>
<ITEM>documented in a reference manual</ITEM></LIST></ITEM>
<ITEM>Tutorials for general and specialized audiences (in progress)</ITEM>
<ITEM>Sample texts (in progress)</ITEM></LIST> ... <EMPH>but no
software (yet)</EMPH></P></DIV>
<DIV TYPE="slide"><HEAD>TEI DTD Structure</HEAD>
<LIST><ITEM>how to make <EMPH>one</EMPH> markup scheme handle
<EMPH>infinite</EMPH> variety of requirements and interests</ITEM>
<ITEM>all texts are alike</ITEM>
<ITEM>every text is different</ITEM>
<ITEM>similar to the database design problem:  one construct, many
views</ITEM>
<ITEM>each view a selection from the whole</ITEM></LIST></DIV>
<DIV TYPE="slide"><HEAD>How Many DTDs?</HEAD>
<P>How many DTDs are necessary for a project like the TEI?<LIST>
<ITEM><LABEL>one</LABEL> (a <SOCALLED>Prussian</SOCALLED> DTD)</ITEM>
<ITEM><LABEL>none</LABEL> (a <SOCALLED>Waterloo</SOCALLED> DTD)</ITEM>
<ITEM><LABEL>one per document</LABEL> (a <SOCALLED>Californian</SOCALLED>
DTD)</ITEM></LIST></P></DIV>
<DIV TYPE="slide"><HEAD>The TEI DTDs</HEAD>
<LIST><ITEM>a single <TERM>main</TERM> DTD with many faces (a
<SOCALLED>British</SOCALLED> DTD)</ITEM>
<ITEM>many tags (over 400)</ITEM>
<ITEM>organized into <TERM>tag sets</TERM></ITEM>
<ITEM>grouped into <TERM>classes</TERM></ITEM>
<ITEM>several <TERM>auxiliary</TERM> DTDs for specialized
information:<LIST>
<ITEM>writing system / character set</ITEM>
<ITEM>feature system (for feature-structure notation)</ITEM>
<ITEM>tag set documentation</ITEM>
<ITEM>independent, free-standing TEI header</ITEM></LIST></ITEM></LIST></DIV>
<DIV TYPE="slide"><HEAD>Combining Tag Sets</HEAD>
<P>How to combine tag sets?  The how-many-DTDs problem is back.<LIST>
<ITEM>all tag sets, all the time (the <TERM>table d'hote</TERM>
model)</ITEM>
<ITEM>a few pre-selected combinations (the <TERM>combination plate</TERM>
model)</ITEM>
<ITEM>in completely unconstrained abandon (the <TERM>smorgasbord</TERM>
model)</ITEM>
<ITEM>one from column A, two from column B (the <TERM>Chinese menu</TERM>
model)</ITEM></LIST></P></DIV>
<DIV TYPE="slide"><HEAD>The Pizza Model</HEAD>
<EG><![CDATA [
<!ELEMENT pizza - - 
					(base, 
					(tomatoSauce & cheese),
					topping*)
<!ELEMENT base  - -
					(thinCrust | deepdish
             | stuffed) >
<!ELEMENT topping - - 
					(mushrooms | pepperoni 
             | sausage | pepper
             | anchovies | ...) >
]]></EG></DIV>
<DIV TYPE="slide"><HEAD>Selecting Tag Sets</HEAD>
<EG><![CDATA [<!DOCTYPE tei.2 SYSTEM 'tei2.dtd' [
  <!ENTITY % TEI.prose 'INCLUDE' >
  <!ENTITY % TEI.analysis 'INCLUDE' >
  <!ENTITY % TEI.fs 'INCLUDE' >
]>]]></EG></DIV>
<DIV TYPE="slide"><HEAD>Element Classes</HEAD>
<LIST><HEAD>Model classes</HEAD>
<ITEM>share syntactic properties (occur in same position)</ITEM>
<ITEM>may have similar meaning</ITEM></LIST>
<LIST><HEAD>Attribute classes</HEAD>
<ITEM>share attributes</ITEM>
<ITEM>generally have similar meaning</ITEM></LIST>
<P>Both types of class may have subclasses; both have inheritance. 
Both are documented and used to generate the DTD.</P></DIV>
<DIV TYPE="slide"><HEAD>Modifying the TEI DTD</HEAD>
<LIST><ITEM>renaming elements</ITEM>
<ITEM>suppressing elements</ITEM>
<ITEM>adding elements</ITEM>
<ITEM>modifying elements</ITEM>
<ITEM>invoking local modifications</ITEM>
<ITEM>documenting local modifications</ITEM></LIST></DIV></DIV>
<DIV TYPE="slidegrp"><HEAD>TEI Lite</HEAD>
<LIST><ITEM>one of many possible views of the TEI dtd</ITEM>
<ITEM>small, simple</ITEM>
<ITEM>realistic for existing texts, e.g. OTA, Virginia </ITEM>
<ITEM>realistic for  document production, e.g. TEI technical
documentation</ITEM></LIST>

<DIV ID="LT2"><HEAD>The Structure(s) of a TEI Document</HEAD>
<LIST REND="bullets"><ITEM>a text contains a <TERM>header</TERM>
followed by a
<TERM>text</TERM></ITEM>
<ITEM>the header contains:
<LIST REND="hyphens">
<ITEM>a <TERM>file description</TERM> 
containing bibliographic information about the machine-readable  
   text itself, and its source</ITEM>
<ITEM>an <TERM>encoding description</TERM> 
explaining how the electronic text was encoded </ITEM>
<ITEM>a <TERM>profile description</TERM> 
containing further information about the text</ITEM>
<ITEM>a <TERM>revision description</TERM> 
containing version control information about the text </ITEM></LIST></ITEM>
</LIST></DIV>
<DIV ID="LT3"><HEAD>Structure of a TEI <GI>text</GI></HEAD>
<LIST REND="bullets"><ITEM>the text may be <TERM>unitary</TERM> or
<TERM>composite</TERM></ITEM>
<ITEM>a text contains:<LIST REND="hyph">
<ITEM>front matter</ITEM>
<ITEM>back matter</ITEM>
<ITEM>a <TERM>body</TERM> </ITEM>
</LIST></ITEM>
<ITEM>in a composite text, the body is a <TERM>group</TERM> of texts
(or nested groups)</ITEM>
</LIST>
</DIV>

<!-- maybe use diagrams here -->

<DIV ID="LT4"><HEAD>TEI Structures Summarized</HEAD>
<EG REND="boxed"><![CDATA [tei2  :: teiHeader text
text  :: front? (body|group) back?
group :: (text|group)+
teiCorpus :: teiHeader tei2+
]]>
</EG>
</DIV>

<DIV ID="LT4bis"><HEAD>Text divisions</HEAD>
<LIST TYPE="bullets"><ITEM>generic, hierarchic subdivisions</ITEM>
<ITEM><SOCALLED>vanilla</SOCALLED> or numbered</ITEM>
<ITEM><ident>type</ident> attribute</ITEM>
<ITEM>associated <GI>head</GI> and <GI>trailer</GI> elements</ITEM>
</LIST>
</DIV>

<DIV ID="LT5"><HEAD>Global Attributes</HEAD>
<LIST TYPE="bullets">
<ITEM><ident>id</ident> for unique identification</ITEM>
<ITEM><ident>n</ident> for  (non-unique) name or number</ITEM>
<ITEM><ident>rend</ident> for rendition</ITEM>
<ITEM><ident>lang</ident> for language and hence writing-system</ITEM>
</LIST>
<P REND="boxr">Applicable to <EMPH>all</EMPH> elements in TEI
scheme.</P>
<!-- examples here! -->

</DIV>
<div><head>A simple example</head>
<p><eg><![ CDATA [
 
<div0 type='book' n='I' id=JA0100>
<head>Book I.</head>
  <div1 type='chapter' n='1' id=JA0101>
  <head>Of writing lives in general, and particularly of
        Pamela, with a word by the bye of Colley
        Cibber and others.</head>
  <p>It is a trite but true observation, that examples work
        more forcibly on the mind than precepts:  ...
 
        <!-- remainder of chapter 1 here -->
  </div1> 
  <div1 n='2' id=JA0102>
  <head>Of Mr. Joseph Andrews, his birth, parentage,
        education, and great endowments; with a word
        or two concerning ancestors.</head>
  <p>Mr. Joseph Andrews, the hero of our ensuing history,
        was esteemed to be the only son of Gaffar and
        Gammar Andrews, and brother to the illustrious
        Pamela, whose virtue is at present so famous ...
 
        <!-- remainder of chapter 2 here -->
  </div1>
      <!-- remaining chapters of Book 1 here -->
<trailer>The end of the first Book</trailer>
</div0>
<div0 n='II' id=JA0100>
<head>Book II</head>
  <div1 n='1' id=JA0201>
  <head>Of divisions in authors</head>
  <p>There are certain mysteries or secrets in all
        trades, from the highest to the lowest, from
   ....

]]></eg>
</div>
<DIV ID="LT6"><HEAD>Text <SOCALLED>components</SOCALLED></HEAD>
<P>What are divisions composed of?
<LIST TYPE="bullets">
<ITEM><HI REND="bold">prose</HI> is mostly paragraphs (<GI>p</GI>)
</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI REND="bold">verse</HI> is mostly lines (<GI>l</GI>),
sometimes in    hierarchic groups (<GI>lg</GI>)</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI REND="bold">drama</HI> is mostly speeches (<GI>sp</GI>)
containing
<GI>p</GI> or <GI>l</GI> and interspersed with stage directions (<GI>
stage</GI>)</ITEM></LIST></P>
<P>These may be mixed, and may also appear directly within undivided
texts.</P></DIV>
<!-- examples here? -->
<DIV ID="LT8bis"><HEAD>Verse</HEAD>
<LIST><ITEM>lines of verse with <GI>l</GI></ITEM>
<ITEM>groups of lines (stanzas, verse paragraphs, other) with <GI>lg</GI></ITEM></LIST>
<EG><![CDATA [
<lg>
<l>Summer grass &mdash;</l>
<l>all that's left</l>
<l>of warriors' dreams.</l>
</lg>
]]></EG></DIV>
<DIV ID="LT8ter"><HEAD>Drama</HEAD>
<LIST><ITEM>speeches (<GI>sp</GI>)</ITEM>
<ITEM>speaker identifications (<ident>who</ident> attribute on <GI>sp</GI>,
or <GI>speaker</GI>)</ITEM>
<ITEM>stage directions (<GI>stage</GI>)</ITEM></LIST></DIV>
<DIV><HEAD>An Example</HEAD>
<EG><![CDATA [
<stage>Enter Barnardo and Francisco,
two Sentinels, at several doors</stage>
<sp who='Barnardo'><l>Who's there?</l>
<sp who='Francisco'><l>Nay, answer me.  Stand and unfold yourself.</l>
<sp who='Barnardo'><l>Long live the king!</l>
<sp who='Francisco'><l>Barnardo?</l>
<sp who='Barnardo'><l>He.</l>
]]></EG></DIV>
<DIV><HEAD>Revised Example</HEAD>
<P>To capture the metrical reality of one line in several speeches,
use the <ident>part</ident> attribute on each <GI>l</GI>.</P>
<EG><![CDATA [
<sp who='Barn'><l part=i>Who's there?</l>
<sp who='Fran'><l part=f>Nay, answer me.  Stand and unfold yourself.</l>
<sp who='Barn'><l part=i>Long live the king!</l>
<sp who='Fran'><l part=m>Barnardo?</l>
<sp who='Barn'><l part=f>He.</l>
]]></EG></DIV>

<DIV ID="LT7"><HEAD>Phrase level elements include...</HEAD>
<LIST TYPE="bullets">
<ITEM><HI REND="bold">typographically highlighted phrases</HI> 
(emphasis, technical terms, foreign language matter, titles, quoted
matter, linguistically distinct etc.)</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>data-like</HI> (names, numbers, dates, times, addresses)</ITEM>
<ITEM>notes and cross references</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>editorial intervention</HI> (corrections, regularizations,
additions, omissions etc.)</ITEM>
</LIST>
</DIV>
<div><head>Interpreting highlighted material</head>
<p>The <gi>hi</gi> element is used to indicate typographic
highlighting:
<EG><![CDATA [<hi rend=gothic>And this Indenture further witnesseth</hi>
that the said <hi rend=italic>Walter Shandy</hi>, merchant,
in consideration of the said intended marriage ...
]]>
</EG></p>
<p>Where the reason for highlighting is evident, a descriptive tag may
be preferable:
<EG><![CDATA [<seg type=formula>And this Indenture further witnesseth</seg>
that the said <name>Walter Shandy</name>, merchant,
in consideration of the said intended marriage ...
]]>
</div>
<div><head>Foreign language phrases</head>
<p>The <ident>lang</ident> attribute may be attached to any element;
use <gi>foreign</gi> if nothing else is available...
<EG><![CDATA [John has real <foreign lang=fra>savoir-faire</foreign>.

Have you read <title lang=deu>Die Dreigroschenoper</title>?

<mentioned lang=fra>Savoir-faire</mentioned> is French for know-how.

The court issued a writ of <term lang=lat>mandamus</term>.
]]>
</EG></P>
</div>
<DIV ID="LT7bis"><HEAD>Quotations</HEAD>
<LIST><ITEM>inline or display</ITEM>
<ITEM>real quotation, feigned quotation, dialogue</ITEM></LIST>
<EG><![CDATA [
<q>Who-e debel you?</q>
&mdash; he at last said &mdash;
<q>you no speak-e, damme, I kill-e.</q>
And so saying, the lighted tomahawk 
began flourishing about me in the dark.
]]></EG></DIV>

<div><head>Names and other referring strings</head>
<p>The <gi>rs</gi> (referring string) element is used for any kind of
name...
<EG><![CDATA [<q>My dear <rs type=person>Mr. Bennet</rs>, </q>
said his lady to him one day, <q>have you heard
that <rs type=place>Netherfield Park</rs> is let
at last?</q>
]]></eg></p>
<p>... and also for anaphors (which may be resolved by the <ident>key</ident>
attribute)
<EG><![CDATA [  <q>My dear <rs type=person key=BENM1>Mr. Bennet</rs>,
  </q> said <rs type=person key=BENM2>his lady</rs>
  to him one day, <q>have you heard that
  <rs type=place key=NETP1>Netherfield Park</rs>
  is let at last?</q>
]]>
</EG>
</div>

<DIV ID="LT9"><HEAD>Cross References</HEAD>
<p><hi>Within</hi> the current document...
<LIST><ITEM>
<GI>ptr</GI> (empty element)</ITEM>
<ITEM><GI>ref</GI> (with content)
<EG><![CDATA [
    See especially <ref target=SEC12>
    section 12 on page 34</ref>.
 
    See especially <ptr target=SEC12>.
]]></EG></ITEM>
<ITEM>target is most conveniently an identifier (<ident>id</ident>
value)
<EG><![CDATA [
    ...
    see especially <ptr target=SEC12>.
    ...
    <div1 id=SEC12>
    <head>Concerning Identifiers...
    ...
]]></EG></ITEM>
<ITEM>Together, these provide simple hypertext capability.</ITEM></LIST>
</DIV>
<DIV><HEAD>Extended Pointers</HEAD>
<p><hi>Outwith</hi>the current document...
<LIST>
<ITEM><GI>xptr</GI> (empty element) or
<GI>xref</GI> (with content)
</ITEM>
<item>target document is specified by <ident>doc</ident> attribute</item>
<item>... and as a <term>location ladder</term>
</item></list>
<EG><![CDATA [
see especially <xptr doc=doc2 from="ID (SEC12)"> 

see especially <xptr doc=doc2 
from="DESCENDANT (2 DIV1) (4 P)
      CHILD (1 QUOTE LANG LAT)">.]]></EG>

<p>Together, these provide full hypertext capability.
</DIV>

<DIV ID="LT8"><HEAD>Boundary Points</HEAD>

<P>Texts are not always neatly hierarchic:</P>
<LIST TYPE="bullets"><ITEM>page and line breaks (<GI>pb</GI>, <GI>lb</GI>,
and <GI>cb</GI>)</ITEM>
<ITEM>generic <GI>milestone</GI> element  </ITEM>
<ITEM>requires left-to-right processing, may not fit well into
hierarchical model of SGML and SGML software</ITEM>
</LIST>
<eg><![ CDATA [
<p>I wrote to Moor House and to Cambridge immediately, to
say what I had done: fully explaining also why I had thus
acted.  Diana and <pb ed=ED1 n='475'> Mary approved the step
unreservedly.  Dia<pb ed=ED2 n='464'>na announced that she 
would just give me time to get over the honeymoon, and 
then she would come and see me.
]]></eg>

</DIV>
<DIV ID="LT11"><HEAD>Bibliographic References</HEAD>

<P>Use simple <GI>bibl</GI> with subcomponents:
<LIST>
<ITEM><GI>respStmt</GI> (for any kind of responsibility)</ITEM>
<ITEM>or <GI>author</GI>, <GI>editor</GI>, etc.</ITEM>
<ITEM><GI>title</GI> with optional <ident>level</ident> attribute</ITEM>
<ITEM><GI>imprint</GI> groups publication details</ITEM>
<ITEM><GI>biblScope</GI> adds page references etc.</ITEM>
</LIST>
</P>
<P>Full Guidelines have more detailed structured elements
<GI>biblStruct</GI> and <GI>biblFull</GI></P>
<P>Use <GI>listBibl</GI> for list of references</P></DIV>
<DIV ID="LT11bis"><HEAD>Omissions, Deletions, Additions</HEAD>
<P>Various types of scribal, editorial, and impersonal  changes can
be tagged:<LIST>
<ITEM>omission by transcriber (<GI>gap</GI>)</ITEM>
<ITEM>cancellation in source or by editor (<GI>del</GI>)</ITEM>
<ITEM>insertion in source or by editor (<GI>add</GI>, <GI>supplied</GI>)</ITEM>
<ITEM>material uncertain because illegible (<GI>unclear</GI>)</ITEM>
<ITEM>physical damage to text carrier (<GI>damage</GI>)</ITEM></LIST></P></DIV>
<div><head>Editorial Correction and Normalization</head>
<p>An encoder may choose to record both the original and a correction
or normalization:
<EG><![CDATA [
 ... for his nose was as sharp as a pen and 
 <reg sic="a'">he</reg>
 <corr sic='table' ed=Gifford>babbl'd</corr> of green
 <reg sic='feelds'>fields</reg>
]]>
</EG>
</div>

<DIV ID="LT9bis"><HEAD>Notes</HEAD>

<p><EMPH>Notes</EMPH> of any kind (editorial or authorial) are
tagged as <GI>note</GI>s:
<list>
<ITEM>in-line or out of line: (use <ident>place</ident> value to
specify)
<EG><![CDATA [<lg>
<l>The self-same moment I could pray
<l>And from my neck so free
<l>The albatross fell off, and sank
<l>Like lead into the sea.
<note type=auth place=margin>
The spell begins to break.</note>
</lg>
]]></EG></ITEM>
<ITEM>target is most conveniently an identifier (<ident>id</ident>
value), functions like pointer</ITEM>
</LIST>
</DIV>
<DIV ID="LT10"><HEAD>Lists</HEAD>
<LIST>
<ITEM>for lists of any kind (use <ident>type</ident> attribute to
distinguish)</ITEM>
<ITEM>use <GI>label</GI> for two-column lists or as alternative to
<ident>n</ident> attribute</ITEM>
<ITEM>may be nested as necessary</ITEM>
</LIST>
</DIV>
<div><head>Figures and graphics</head>
<list>
<item>The presence of a graphic is indicated by the <gi>figure</gi> element</item>
<item>The title of the graphic is tagged as a <gi>head</gi></item>
<item>A description of the graphic may be supplied (as a <gi>figDesc</gi>)
for use by software unable to render the graphic</item>
<item>The graphic itself may be specified as an external entity</item>
</list>
<p>For example...
<EG><![CDATA [  <figure entity=fezziPic>
   <head>Mr Fezziwig's Ball</head>
   <figdesc>A Cruikshank engraving showing Mr Fezziwig leading
      a group of revellers.</figdesc>
   </figure>
]]></eg>
</div>

<DIV ID="LT12"><HEAD>Character Encoding Recommendations</HEAD>
<LIST TYPE="bullets">
<ITEM>for interchange, use ISO 646 subset</ITEM>
<ITEM>extend, using standard entity sets or transliteration</ITEM>
<ITEM>document transliteration scheme with formal <TERM>Writing
System Declaration</TERM></ITEM></LIST>
<P>The WSD maps grapheme, entity name (private or public), AFII
value, ISO 10646 value, prose description, bitmap</P>
</DIV>

<!-- nothing on analysis here -->

<DIV ID="LT13"><HEAD>The TEI Header</HEAD>
<LIST TYPE="bullets"><ITEM>mandatory</ITEM>
<ITEM>independently interchangeable</ITEM>
<ITEM>support for librarians</ITEM>
<ITEM>support for corpus builders</ITEM>
</LIST></DIV>

<DIV ID="LT14"><HEAD>The File Description contains...</HEAD>
<LIST TYPE="bullets"><ITEM>five ISBD <TERM>areas</TERM>:
<LIST>
<ITEM>titleStmt</ITEM>
<ITEM>editionStmt</ITEM>
<ITEM>extent</ITEM>
<ITEM>publicationStmt</ITEM></LIST></ITEM>
<ITEM>sourceDesc</ITEM>
<ITEM>notesStmt</ITEM></LIST>
</DIV>

<DIV ID="LT15"><HEAD>The Encoding Description contains...</HEAD>
<LIST TYPE="bullets"><ITEM>projectDesc</ITEM>
<ITEM>samplingDecl</ITEM>
<ITEM>editorialDecl</ITEM>
<ITEM>tagsDecl</ITEM>
<ITEM>refsDecl</ITEM>
<ITEM>classDecl</ITEM></LIST>
</DIV>

<DIV ID="LT16"><HEAD>The Profile Description contains...</HEAD>
<P>miscellaneous additional information such as
<LIST>
<ITEM><GI>creation</GI> </ITEM>
<ITEM><GI>langUsage</GI></ITEM>
<ITEM><GI>textClass</GI></ITEM></LIST>
</P>
<P>plus, when the corpus tagset is chosen,
<LIST TYPE="bullets">
<ITEM>textDesc</ITEM>
<ITEM>particDesc</ITEM>
<ITEM>settingDesc</ITEM></LIST>
</P></DIV></DIV>
<DIV TYPE="slidegrp"><HEAD>Practical Issues</HEAD>
<DIV TYPE="slide"><HEAD>Practical Issues</HEAD>
<LIST><ITEM>Project planning</ITEM>
<ITEM>Software</ITEM>
<ITEM>Reasons not to use the TEI</ITEM>
<ITEM>For more information ...</ITEM></LIST></DIV>
<DIV TYPE="slide"><HEAD>Project Management</HEAD>
<LIST><ITEM>The steps of a project:<LIST>
<ITEM>clarify goals</ITEM>
<ITEM>select sample and analyse documents</ITEM>
<ITEM>specify markup policy</ITEM>
<ITEM>encode the texts</ITEM>
<ITEM>enrich, reuse, retarget, ...</ITEM></LIST></ITEM></LIST></DIV>
<DIV TYPE="slide"><HEAD>Setting Markup Policy</HEAD>
<LIST><ITEM>design a new DTD from scratch?</ITEM>
<ITEM>select a subset of an existing DTD?</ITEM>
<ITEM>specify recognition criteria for elements (when do we tag a
proper noun?  When do we tag place names?)</ITEM>
<ITEM>plan markup stages:<LIST>
<ITEM>markup which <EMPH>must</EMPH> be included at data capture
stage</ITEM>
<ITEM>markup software can generate</ITEM>
<ITEM>markup requiring human intervention</ITEM>
<ITEM>semi-manual / software-assisted markup</ITEM></LIST></ITEM></LIST></DIV>
<DIV TYPE="slide"><HEAD>Layering Information</HEAD>
<P>SGML allows the same passage to contain:<LIST>
<ITEM>orthographic transcription</ITEM>
<ITEM>pointer(s) to digital recording</ITEM>
<ITEM>pointer(s) to image</ITEM>
<ITEM>markup of proper nouns, dates, times, etc.</ITEM>
<ITEM>part-of-speech and morphological tagging</ITEM>
<ITEM>syntactic analysis</ITEM>
<ITEM>discourse analysis</ITEM>
<ITEM>cross references to other material on the topic</ITEM>
<ITEM>editorial commentary and annotation</ITEM>
<ITEM>etc., etc., etc.</ITEM></LIST></P></DIV>
<DIV TYPE="slide"><HEAD>Some Implications for Projects</HEAD>
<LIST><ITEM>data representation is fundamental:  think ahead</ITEM>
<ITEM>TEI conformance means less --- and more --- than you might
think</ITEM>
<ITEM>get your fingers dirty</ITEM>
<ITEM><EMPH>record</EMPH> what you do:  data representation is
fundamental </ITEM></LIST></DIV>
